=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked last week</a> about the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26026573.275653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMDcvdGhlLXRydW1wLXNwYW=
MtcGl0Y2gtaXMtd2VpcmQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIxMzIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lb=
WFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMjEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1t=
b25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd2b92c64" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Trump SPAC PIPE</a=
>. A quick recap: Donald Trump has a vague sketch of a media company called=
 Trump Media &amp; Technology Group (TMTG). TMTG is a private company and t=
here is almost no public information about its business, finances, executiv=
es, etc. In October, TMTG announced a merger with a special purpose acquisi=
tion company (SPAC) called Digital World Acquisition Corp. (DWAC), which wi=
ll contribute about $293 million of cash to TMTG in exchange for TMTG stock=
. DWAC is currently a public company; it raised stock from the public by se=
lling shares at $10 each, and upon the announcement of the TMTG deal its st=
ock shot up. It closed at $56.02 on Friday.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Traditionally SPAC deals are accompanied by private investments in public =
equity (PIPEs), in which big institutional investors agree to buy stock in =
the combined company at the time of the SPAC merger. Often=C2=A0the PIPE in=
vestors invest on the same terms as the SPAC investors, buying stock in the=
 new company at $10 per share, but where (as here) the stock is up a lot in=
 anticipation of the merger, the PIPE investors might <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26026573.275653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMjMvdGVzbGEtcml2YWwtbHVjaWQtbW=
90b3JzLXBhaWQtYS1wcmljZS1mb3ItaXRzLXNwYWMtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjEzMjFfTU9OR=
VlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0y=
MTEyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBee31d020" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> agree to a higher price</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">TMTG =
and DWAC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26026573.=
275653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ2xvYmVuZXdzd2lyZS5jb20vbmV3cy1yZWxlYXNlLzIwMjEvMTIv=
MDQvMjM0NjEzOS8wL2VuL1RydW1wLU1lZGlhLVRlY2hub2xvZ3ktR3JvdXAtQ29ycC1hbmQtRGl=
naXRhbC1Xb3JsZC1BY3F1aXNpdGlvbi1Db3JwLUFubm91bmNlLTEtQmlsbGlvbi1QSVBFLUludm=
VzdG1lbnQtaW4tQ29tbWl0dGVkLUNhcGl0YWwtdG8tRnVuZC1CdXNpbmVzcy5odG1s/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB76ee5d54" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">announced a $1 billion PIPE</a> on Satur=
day, Dec. 4. The price was a bit weird. Nominally it is $33.60 per share: T=
he PIPE investors put in $1 billion and get back 29.8 million shares ($1,00=
0,000,000 divided by $33.60). But it is subject to downward adjustment: The=
 actual number of shares that the PIPE investors get is only fixed after th=
e SPAC merger closes.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot will happen bet=
ween now and when the SPAC merger closes. TMTG and DWAC will have to file a=
 merger proxy with extensive financial and business information about TMTG.=
 Perhaps that information will be, you know, bad. Perhaps investors will re=
ad the proxy and say =E2=80=9Chuh this company has no real business plan=E2=
=80=9D and the stock will drop. Or not, I don=E2=80=99t know, I am not sure=
 I=E2=80=99d bet on the stock dropping due to a lack of business plan; you =
can read TMTG=E2=80=99s current investor deck <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/26026573.275653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmN=
oaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDk2MzUvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMzQ4NTkzL2QyNDI0NDJkZXg5OT=
IuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9343dc71" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">here</a>, and it is not =
exactly replete with business planning. Still the point is that there is so=
me=C2=A0<em>risk=C2=A0</em>of the stock dropping.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">But the PIPE investors are protected against this in two ways. First=
, TMTG and DWAC have promised the PIPE investors that they=E2=80=99ll be ab=
le to sell the stock the minute the merger closes. Ordinarily in SPAC deals=
,=C2=A0the company agrees to file a registration statement with the Securit=
ies and Exchange Commission and work to get the SEC to approve it, so that =
the PIPE investors can legally resell their shares. But usually that happen=
s after closing, and you can't count on rushing the SEC. In this deal, TMTG=
 and DWAC have promised to get the registration statement effective=C2=A0<e=
m>before=C2=A0</em>closing, and in fact it is a condition to the closing of=
 the PIPE. The PIPE investors only have to put up their money if they can i=
mmediately turn around and resell their shares.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The second protection is that the price of the PIPE is =E2=80=9Csubjec=
t to downward adjustment.=E2=80=9D When the merger closes and TMTG is publi=
c, it will look at the average closing price over the next 10 trading days,=
 and use that to compute the final price of the PIPE. If the stock trades a=
t $56 or above after closing, there will be no adjustment, and the PIPE inv=
estors will buy stock at $33.60 per share. If it trades below $56, though, =
the PIPE investors will buy stock at a 40% discount to whatever the average=
 price is: If it trades at $45, they=E2=80=99ll pay $27 per share. (Effecti=
vely, they'll get more shares =E2=80=94=C2=A037 million, at $27 per share =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0for their billion dollars.) But this is floored at $10: If t=
he stock trades at $16.67 or below (including if it trades below $10), the =
PIPE investors will buy at $10 per share.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The result is that the PIPE investors are committing $1 billion of mon=
ey, but taking very little risk and getting very richly rewarded. They can =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and, I expect, will =E2=80=94=C2=A0sell their stock as soon =
as the merger closes and TMTG is public, and they=E2=80=99ll sell at a huge=
 guaranteed profit because they will buy their stock at a 40% discount to t=
he stock price=C2=A0<em>at the time they pay for it</em>. Still, some risk:=
 If the stock is below $10 by the time the deal closes, they will lose mone=
y on the trade.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or that is what I said last=
 week, but the trade is <em>actually even=C2=A0better=C2=A0</em>for the PIP=
E investors? Because here is the trade they can do:</p><ol style=3D"list-st=
yle-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;"><em>Short DWAC stock now, </em>locking in a sale=C2=A0pri=
ce of=C2=A0about $56 per share.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Bu=
y back the stock at closing, from TMTG/DWAC, at a maximum purchase price of=
 $33.60.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Make $22.40 per share gua=
ranteed.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ordinarily, if you short sto=
ck in Trump=E2=80=99s thing at $56, you run the risk that it will go up to =
$100 and you=E2=80=99ll lose a ton of money. But if you have committed to t=
he PIPE, TMTG and DWAC have agreed to sell you shares at $33.60 (subject to=
 <em>downward=C2=A0</em>adjustment), so that risk is off the table. If the =
stock goes up, you buy at $33.60. If the stock stays flat, you buy at $33.6=
0. If the stock goes down, you buy at a 40% discount to the market price. I=
f it goes down to $20, you buy at $12. If it goes down to $16.67, your pric=
e is floored and you buy at $10, but that=E2=80=99s fine=C2=A0<em>if you al=
ready sold at $56</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say y=
ou have committed $100 million to the PIPE. At the cap price, this means yo=
u will get about=C2=A03 million shares ($100 million divided by $33.60). So=
 you sell all those shares today, at about $56 per share, for $167 million.=
 Then at the closing of the PIPE you put in your $100 million, get back at =
least 3 million shares, and deliver them to your stock lenders to close out=
 your short position. You are left with a $67 million profit. If the stock =
goes down, and is below $56 after the merger closes, you will get more shar=
es =E2=80=94=C2=A0as many as 10 million, if the stock is at $16.67 or below=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then you can sell those too for some extra cash.[1] But=
 the $67 million is guaranteed no matter what the stock does.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to point out that=C2=A0<em>this is explicitly c=
ontemplated by the deal documents</em>. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26026573.275653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9Bc=
mNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDk2MzUvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMzQ4NTkzL2QyNDI0NDJkZXgx=
MDEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf4b98ff4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Section 3.1(bb)</a> of =
the Securities Purchase Agreement that the PIPE investors signed with DWAC =
(emphasis added):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Acknowledgmen=
t Regarding Purchaser=E2=80=99s Trading Activity. Anything in this Agreemen=
t or elsewhere herein to the contrary notwithstanding (except for Sections =
3.2(g), 4.12 and 4.15 hereof), it is understood and acknowledged by the Com=
pany that: (i) none of the Purchasers has been asked by the Company to agre=
e, nor, to the knowledge of the Company, has any Purchaser agreed, to desis=
t from purchasing or selling, long and/or short, securities of the Company,=
 or =E2=80=9Cderivative=E2=80=9D securities based on securities issued by t=
he Company or to hold the Securities for any specified term, (ii) past or f=
uture open market or other transactions by any Purchaser, specifically incl=
uding, without limitation, Short Sales or =E2=80=9Cderivative=E2=80=9D tran=
sactions, before or after the closing of this or future private placement t=
ransactions, may negatively impact the market price of the Company=E2=80=99=
s publicly-traded securities, (iii) <strong>after the execution of this Agr=
eement, any Purchaser, and counter-parties in =E2=80=9Cderivative=E2=80=9D =
transactions to which any such Purchaser is a party, directly or indirectly=
, may have a =E2=80=9Cshort=E2=80=9D position in the Common Stock</strong> =
and (iv) each Purchaser shall not be deemed to have any affiliation with or=
 control over any arm=E2=80=99s length counter-party in any =E2=80=9Cderiva=
tive=E2=80=9D transaction.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tha=
t is, DWAC <em>agreed that the PIPE investors can=C2=A0short DWAC stock rig=
ht now</em>.[2] This is a very unusual provision in SPAC PIPEs; most purcha=
se agreements specifically say that the investors are=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</e=
m>allowed to short.[3] In the Trump SPAC PIPE, they specifically=C2=A0<em>a=
re=C2=A0</em>allowed to.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now! A coupl=
e of things. First, there are risks to this trade. One risk is that it migh=
t be expensive to borrow DWAC stock, it=E2=80=99s a meme stock, the price c=
ould go up, borrow could be recalled, and you could be forced to cover your=
 short at a loss before the merger closes. If you make it to closing, you=
=E2=80=99re guaranteed to be able to buy the stock for $33.60 for a risk-fr=
ee profit, but you had better be sure that your stock borrow is locked up u=
ntil then. And closing =E2=80=94=C2=A0which requires writing a public discl=
osure document that satisfies SEC rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0could be a long way =
away.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another risk is, I say =E2=80=9Cyou=
=E2=80=99re guaranteed to be able to buy the stock for $33.60,=E2=80=9D but=
 that depends on DWAC and TMTG honoring the commitments in the contract and=
, you know, who knows. Donald Trump has been known to re-trade on deals.[4]=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Beyond the risk of perhaps getting short a=
 meme stock and then being forced to cover prematurely, there are legal ris=
ks. The main one is: If TMTG hired an investment bank to sell $1 billion of=
 stock into the market right now, today, with the extremely limited public =
information about TMTG=E2=80=99s business and finances that is currently av=
ailable, that investment bank would definitely be breaking the law. (Specif=
ically it would be violating <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/26026573.275653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90=
ZXh0LzE1Lzc3ZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcc7ed989" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Section 5 of the =
Securities Act of 1933</a>, which requires sales of stock to be registered.=
) If this transaction consists effectively of TMTG hiring a bunch of PIPE i=
nvestors to sell $1 billion of stock into the market right now, with the de=
livery of the stock to the investors in a few months, there is a risk that =
those investors are also legally underwriters of unregistered stock, and wi=
ll get in trouble. (Not legal advice!) The fact that the transaction explic=
itly acknowledges that they might be doing this suggests that they=E2=80=99=
re not too worried about the legal risk, but the SEC =E2=80=94=C2=A0which d=
oesn=E2=80=99t like SPACs anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0might disagree.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact short interest in DWAC stock does not seem=
 to be especially high =E2=80=94=C2=A0certainly not the full 29.8 million s=
hares underlying the PIPE =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the volume over the past week =
also does not suggest that the PIPE investors have been selling all that he=
avily.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still! It seems like they could; it =
seems like the deal was=C2=A0<em>specifically set up so they could</em>. It=
 was specifically set up to let them buy stock at $33.60 and lock in a sale=
s price, today, in the $40s or $50s. It was specifically set up to be guara=
nteed free money for the PIPE investors.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
ere has been a lot of writing about the Trump SPAC PIPE that suggests that =
the investors in this PIPE are somehow doing Donald Trump an under-the-tabl=
e favor, that this is a story about secret money in politics. <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26026573.275653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
ubW90aGVyam9uZXMuY29tL3BvbGl0aWNzLzIwMjEvMTIvdHJ1bXAtZHdhYy1zcGFjLXNlYy8/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB220e0fc0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">For instance</a>:</p><blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not only was a big PIPE investment not announce=
d when the partnership with Trump was revealed, now that it has been announ=
ced, the names of the investors have not been made public. That=E2=80=99s b=
ecause each investor has been limited to controlling no more than 4.99 perc=
ent of the voting stock, just under the Securities and Exchange Commission=
=E2=80=99s threshold requiring anyone controlling 5 percent or more to be i=
dentified publicly in filings.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=
=9CThis PIPE is structured so that the identity of the PIPE investors may n=
ot be known for a long time, if ever,=E2=80=9D Rodrigues says.=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While the public and general shareholders don=E2=
=80=99t know who the PIPE investors are, Trump apparently does. In fact, Re=
uters reported last week that Trump has been personally calling certain pot=
ential PIPE investors, trying to get them to commit to a $100 million inves=
tment, which heightens a potential for a conflict of interest=E2=80=94only =
Trump would know what other interests he might have to serve.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAre they individuals or companies or countrie=
s that have a stake in something that he could affect as president?=E2=80=
=9D Kathleen Clark, a professor of legal ethics at Washington University in=
 St. Louis says. =E2=80=9CYes, of course they are, whoever they are, but I =
think the bigger question right now, is: Will we ever know their identities=
?=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, first of all,=
 yes, of course we will know their identities: The PIPE investors will all =
be listed as selling shareholders in the registration statement, which will=
=C2=A0be filed before the merger closes.[5]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>But second, I think the whole premise here is wrong. If you agreed to inve=
st in Donald Trump=E2=80=99s $1 billion SPAC PIPE, it is not because you wa=
nt to=C2=A0<em>donate=C2=A0</em>money to Donald Trump, to do=C2=A0<em>him=
=C2=A0</em>a favor. It is because, in exchange for your investment, you wil=
l get Donald Trump meme stock that you can=C2=A0<em>immediately=C2=A0</em>s=
ell to retail investors at a huge guaranteed profit. He is doing=C2=A0<em>y=
ou=C2=A0</em>a favor! I assume that the PIPE investors include a lot of Tru=
mp friends who are very grateful to be in the deal. Because it=E2=80=99s fr=
ee money!</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" c=
