</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because DWAC is a SPAC, it has warrant=
s outstanding. Each warrant represents the right to buy one share of stock,=
=C2=A0<em>after=C2=A0</em>the merger with TMTG closes, for $11.50. The warr=
ants (ticker DWACW) closed on Friday at $18.35. The stock (DWAC) closed at =
$56.02.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some simple arithmetic reveals that=
 $11.50 + $18.35 =3D $29.85, and $29.85 &lt; $56.02. If you want to get exp=
osure to DWAC/TMTG, you can buy one share for $56.02, or you can buy one wa=
rrant (to buy one share for $11.50) for $18.35. The total per-share cost of=
 the warrant, $29.85, is $26.17 lower than the going price of the stock.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is anomalous! But not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=
=A0</em>anomalous, for meme-y SPAC warrants. (We talked about a similar sit=
uation in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26026573=
.275653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDc=
tMjEvcGVvcGxlLWxvdmVkLW5pa29sYS1idXQtbm90LWl0cy13YXJyYW50cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMj=
