G1fdGVybT0yMTEyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B95f61508" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> Nikola Corp. warrants</a> last year.) The basic situati=
on is that the stock is meme-y, salient, beloved by retail investors, and h=
igh, while the warrants are a bit weirder, more niche, traded by hedge fund=
s, and lower. You=E2=80=99d think that there'd be an arbitrage between them=
, but it=E2=80=99s imperfect. You can=E2=80=99t exercise the warrants now =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0you=C2=A0have to wait until after closing =E2=80=94=C2=A0so =
you can=E2=80=99t just capture the $26.17 difference now. The classic way t=
o capture the difference is to buy a warrant and=C2=A0<em>short </em>a shar=
e of stock,[6] but that is risky for the reasons it=E2=80=99s risky for the=
 PIPE investors (limited expensive stock borrow that might be recalled, etc=
.). I suppose the point is that there are lots of Trump-SPAC trades that lo=
ok like free money, but be careful with them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Elsewhere in Trump-SPAC warrant trades that look like free money, <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26026573.275653/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8xMi8wOS9idXNpbmVzcy90cnVtcC1zcGFjLXN0b2NrLmh=
